{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609630"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:49:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:49:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16112"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16112"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.4,0.2,0.16,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8803"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63946"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8803"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16112"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49376"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8599"},{"type":"tags","id":"8605"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21011"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21014"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63946"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, primordial germ cells undergo a complex migratory journey from their site of origin to reach the developing gonads.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryonic origin of primordial germ cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ectoderm derivatives","Endoderm derivatives","Mesoderm derivatives","Neural crest derivatives","Notochord derivatives"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPrimordial germ cells originate from \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoderm derivatives\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically from epiblast cells that migrate into the yolk sac endoderm during gastrulation. These cells later migrate through the dorsal mesentery to reach the developing gonads.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEctoderm derivatives\u003C/strong\u003E - While ectoderm gives rise to the nervous system and epidermis, it does not form primordial germ cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesoderm derivatives\u003C/strong\u003E - Although the gonads develop from mesoderm, the germ cells themselves are not of mesodermal origin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural crest derivatives\u003C/strong\u003E - Neural crest cells give rise to multiple cell types but not primordial germ cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENotochord derivatives\u003C/strong\u003E - The notochord is important for embryonic patterning but does not give rise to germ cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the endodermal origin of primordial germ cells is important for comprehending their unique developmental pathway and eventual contribution to gamete formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primordial germ cells originate from epiblast cells in the yolk sac endoderm during early embryonic development.","Despite their endodermal origin, primordial germ cells migrate through the primitive streak to reach the developing gonads."],"references":["Richardson BE, Lehmann R. Mechanisms guiding primordial germ cell migration: strategies from different organisms. Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol. 2010 Jan;11(1):37-49. d